  "prompt": "How has legislation evolved to combat money laundering?",
  "response": "Legislation to combat money laundering has evolved significantly over the past few decades:\n\n1. Early Stages\n- Bank Secrecy Act (1970) in the US\n- Initial focus on financial record-keeping\n- Limited scope of financial institutions covered\n\n2. International Developments\n- FATF (Financial Action Task Force) established in 1989\n- Created global standards for anti-money laundering (AML)\n- Developed recommendations for national legal frameworks\n\n3. Key Legislative Milestones\n- US Patriot Act (2001)\n- Enhanced reporting requirements\n- Expanded definition of money laundering\n- Increased penalties for non-compliance\n\n4. Technological Adaptations\n- Regulations addressing digital currencies\n- Enhanced customer due diligence requirements\n- Risk-based monitoring approaches\n\n5. Recent Trends\n- Increased transparency requirements\n- Beneficial ownership disclosure\n- Stricter cryptocurrency regulations\n- Enhanced international cooperation\n- More complex compliance mechanisms\n\n6. Global Regulatory Convergence\n- Growing standardization of AML practices\n- Shared information networks\n- Coordinated enforcement strategies\n\nThe legislation has progressively become more comprehensive, technology-aware, and internationally coordinated.",
